      "@type": "Claim",
      "@id": "#claim-5b",
      "claimNumber": "5b",
      "shortName": "role-bifurcation",
      "title": "Roles bifurcate in large enterprise and regulated contexts",
      "statement": "In large enterprises and regulated industries, AI may produce role bifurcation rather than convergence: a smaller tier of elite generalists who define harnesses and systems, and a larger tier of commoditized execution roles whose tasks are increasingly AI-mediated and narrowly scoped.",
      "rationale": "Large organizations have structural incentives to specialize and stratify. AI may reinforce this by making junior execution cheaper (not eliminated), while concentrating judgment and autonomy at the top among those who define the harnesses, specs, and validation regimes. (The distinct question of whether automating entry-level work narrows the senior-talent pipeline is now tracked in Claim 5c.)",
      "status": "Proposed",
      "statusLastChanged": "v1.0.0",
      "supportingSignals": [
        "ADP payroll data showing routine cognitive tasks declining faster than manual ones, with larger effects in bigger firms.",
        "Stanford \"Canaries in the Coal Mine\" paper: specific task categories declining while orchestration roles grow—but growth is concentrated at senior levels.",
        "PwC 2026 two-track signal: \"professionalised\" judgement-tier roles growing ~2x faster (42% faster wage growth) than \"democratised\" execution-tier roles.",
        "Senior engineers absorbing disproportionate review/verification burden from AI-augmented output (emergent stratification)."
      ],
      "challenges": [
        "NY Fed research: aggregate employment stable so far; macro data does not yet show bifurcation.",
        "MIT Sloan analysis: AI effects are gradual, task-specific, and often complementary.",
        "Some enterprises report *increased* junior hiring for AI-augmented roles (data labeling, prompt engineering, validation)."
      ],
      "evaluationCriteria": [
        "Junior-to-senior hiring ratio changes in enterprises with >500 employees",
        "Skill distribution changes within large engineering orgs (breadth vs depth)",
        "Wage distribution shifts (compression vs polarization)",
        "Evidence that the top tier's authority derives specifically from harness/spec/validation authorship (vs generic seniority)"
      ],
      "observations": [
        {
          "@type": "Observation",
          "period": "Q2 2026",
          "notes": [
            "**Split applied.** The \"broken bottom rung\" / pipeline-narrowing limb was separated into [Claim 5c](./claim-5c-broken-bottom-rung.md), where new Tier A evidence (Ide; Stanford AI Index) supports it. This claim retains the *harness-defining bifurcation* mechanism.",
            "**Bifurcation mechanism remains under-evidenced.** PwC 2026 (Tier B, 1B+ ads) shows a genuine two-track market (professionalised vs democratised roles), supporting stratification — but no Tier A source evidences the specific \"elite generalists who *define harnesses*\" framing; that limb is still interpretive. Status held at **Proposed**.",
            "An adversarial verification panel reviewed a proposed promotion this cycle and **refuted it 2-0**: the new Tier A evidence supports the pipeline sub-limb (now 5c), not the bifurcation mechanism, and the Davenport survey (~90% of hiring freezes anticipatory vs 2% tied to realized AI) undercuts causal attribution. Conservative default applied: no promotion."
          ]
        },
        {
          "@type": "Observation",
          "period": "Q1 2026",
          "notes": [
            "The bifurcation narrative gained traction in Q1 2026 industry discourse, but remains under-evidenced at Tier A level.",
            "No longitudinal labor dataset yet confirms or refutes bifurcation in enterprise contexts specifically.",
            "This claim is deliberately positioned as \"Proposed\" to flag it for rigorous tracking without overstating confidence."
          ]
        }
      ],
